  "prompt": "What I can do now because my 18 year will be completed in 17 January 2017. and most companies age limit is 18 year as on aug 2016?",
  "response": "Okay, I understand. You're turning 18 in January 2017, and many companies hiring for jobs in August 2016 require applicants to be 18 *by* August 2016. This presents a challenge because you're not yet 18. Here's a breakdown of your options and what you can realistically do:\n\n**Things You CAN'T Do:**\n\n*   **Apply for jobs specifically requiring 18+ as of August 2016 and misrepresent your age.** This is generally considered fraudulent and could have serious consequences.\n\n**Things You CAN Do:**\n\n*   **Focus on Opportunities That Don't Have the Age Restriction:**\n    *   **Look for jobs with a later age requirement date:** Some companies might specify \"must be 18 by [later date]\" or simply \"must be 18.\" These would be fine.\n    *   **Consider jobs without age restrictions (if any):** Some entry-level positions might not explicitly require 18+ (though this is rare). Read the requirements carefully.\n    *   **Target Companies with Rolling Hiring:** If the company hires throughout the year, you might be able to apply closer to your birthday and meet the age requirement.\n\n*   **Gain Experience and Skills:** Even if you can't get *that specific* job right now, focus on building your resume and skills. This will make you a more attractive candidate later.\n    *   **Volunteer:** Volunteering demonstrates initiative, responsibility, and teamwork.  It's a great way to gain experience in different fields.\n    *   **Take Online Courses:** Platforms like Coursera, edX, and Udemy offer courses in a wide range of subjects.  Pick something relevant to the kind of work you're interested in.\n    *   **Work on Personal Projects:**  If you're interested in coding, build a website or app.  If you're interested in writing, start a blog or contribute to online publications.\n    *   **Freelance (if possible):** Depending on the type of work, you might be able to do freelance work online.  Check the terms and conditions of the platforms and any age restrictions.\n\n*   **Networking:**\n    *   **Informational Interviews:** Reach out to people working in fields you're interested in and ask if you can have a brief informational interview.  This is a chance to learn about their work and get advice.\n    *   **Attend Industry Events (if any):**  Look for workshops, conferences, or meetups in your area related to your interests.\n\n*   **Prepare for Future Job Applications:**\n    *   **Create a Resume:**  Even without a lot of formal work experience, you can highlight your skills, education, volunteer work, and personal projects.\n    *   **Practice Interview Skills:**  Research common interview questions and practice your answers.\n    *   **Research Companies:**  When you find companies you're interested in, learn about their culture, values, and mission.\n\n*   **Check Local Labor Laws:** Familiarize yourself with the labor laws in your area regarding minors (even if you're turning 18 soon). Some restrictions may apply.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Honesty:**  Always be honest about your age and qualifications. It's better to wait until you meet the requirements than to risk getting caught misrepresenting yourself.\n*   **Patience:** It can be frustrating to have to wait, but use this time to your advantage by building your skills and experience.\n*   **Alternative paths:**\n    *   **Internships:** It may be difficult to get a paid internship before turning 18, but it may be possible.\n    *   **Job shadowing:** Shadowing may be an option to explore jobs and experience it.\n\n**In summary, while you can't realistically get a job that specifically requires you to be 18 as of August 2016, you can use this time to build your skills, gain experience, network, and prepare for future job opportunities. When you turn 18, you'll be in a much stronger position to land the job you want.**\n",
